  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Protecting The Right To Have Access To Adequate Housing</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As people move to the cities in search of a better life, the worldwide number of urban slum dwellers has risen to 828 million. In South Africa, this trend is accelerating, driving up the price of land and forcing people into substandard high-cost housing. As a result, poor, vulnerable and marginalised communities living in shacks and temporary housing face threats of eviction and suffer from a lack of basic services, such as water and sanitation. The Legal Resources Centre supports South African slum communities by challenging the State, often through the courts, to meet their obligations. By using, and sometimes setting, legal precedents, errant authorities and exploitative landlords are forced to provide access to affordable housing with adequate basic services. The work also gives communities the confidence and skills they need to lobby for improvements themselves.</narrative>
  </description>
